        "pension_h2": "2. Recommended for these people",
        "pension_rec1": "<strong>Those who want stable retirement and a certain annual return (tax credit):</strong> Pension accounts are a necessity, not an option.",
        "pension_rec2": "<strong>Office workers with a large tax burden at year-end tax settlement:</strong> It is the most certain tool for those who want to reduce the tax they pay every year and receive refunds. When filling the 9 million KRW limit, you can get back up to 1.485 million KRW.",
        "pension_rec3": "<strong>Those who want to prepare long-term retirement funds:</strong> It is suitable for those who want to steadily accumulate for old age after 55, not money to spend right now. It has the effect of forcing savings while receiving benefits given by the state.",
        "pension_rec4": "<strong>Those who want to maximize the compound effect through tax deferral:</strong> Unlike general accounts, you do not pay dividend income tax (15.4%) every time, and you can pay at a low tax rate (3.3~5.5%) when you receive a pension later, so your investment principal grows faster.",

        "pension_h3": "3. 3 Key Tax-Saving Benefits of Pension Accounts",
        "pension_ben1": "<strong>Tax Credit (Immediate Refund):</strong> You get back a certain percentage of the amount you saved immediately from that year's year-end tax settlement. It is essentially like an investment starting with a fixed rate of return.",
        "pension_ben2": "<strong>Tax Deferral (Pushing back the timing of tax payment):</strong> You do not pay tax right now on dividends or capital gains generated during the investment process. This money is reinvested, increasing the compound effect.",
        "pension_ben3": "<strong>Pension Income Tax (Low tax rate application):</strong> When you receive a pension later, you only need to pay a low pension income tax of 3.3~5.5% instead of 15.4% dividend income tax.",

        "pension_h4": "4. Example of Tax Credit Benefit Experience (When paying 9 million KRW per year)",
